Try below:

    # ...
    path('__debug__/', include('debug_toolbar.urls')),

author: Clare
comment_text:
For people on windows who had issues setting the interpreter up and the vscode terminal this is how I sorted it out.

interpreter:

- Commande Palette -> Preferences: Open Workspace Settings (JSON) (This creates the .vscode folder and an empty settings.json file)
- Then add manually "python.defaultInterpreterPath": "**your path **\\Scripts\\python" (I put in "python.pythonPath" first as the video said but when I restarted VSCode I got an error that suggested that "python.defaultInterpreterPath" needed to be used instead. I still have both in the list but not sure if I need both. 
- restart VSCode 

VSCode terminal:

I opened the terminal is VSCode and was getting an error because of what Execution_Policies is set to, I decided to solve it by clicking the down arrow in the top right of the terminal and chose to use Command Prompt instead.

author: Metin Emiroglu
comment_text:
Hey! pipenv itself is not actually a requirement to run Django. Python 3 already provides  virtual environment support. To use it, assuming you are in empty directory:
python -m venv venv # this creates a venv directory
source venv/bin/activate # activates virtual environment on mac/linux or:
\venv\Scripts\activate.bat # activates virtual environment on windows
code .
And you are good to go.

comment_text:
I used Django on a project last year.  I absolutely hated it.  I have never seen a "language" with less coherence.  It looks like it was designed by people who never communicated with each other.  

I've learned a lot of languages over my 30+ years in software; on this job Django was one of three I needed to learn, though I only used it once.
